name: aħənžia
description: Exact counterpart (Words such as ‘’boy” and “girl” tend to be taboo words (probably in order to prevent jinnees from interfering with the children). These often have expressive sound formations, such as the substitution or addition of a phoneme by ħ. Often such word have Arabic roots (e.g. in other Riffian dialects aħāmuš ‘boy’, which contains the Arabic root ħrm ‘be forbidden’, often used in conotations of bastard children. It is difficult to establish an Arabic basis for aħənžia; one could think of Moroccan Arabic xənzir ‘pig’ with the well-attested expressive sound substitutions of a back consonant by ħ and of z by ž. This is however far from certain.)

description: (In Indonesian, jago usually means ‘champion, good athlete’.  It is rarely used with the meaning ‘rooster’, unless modifiying ayam.)

name: itik
description: (Not in common use except regionally; common word is bébék.)

name: terwélu
description: (Used rarely, and mostly by ethnic Javanese.  The common word is kelinci.)

name: arnab
description: (The word is commonly used in Peninsular Malay dialects, but rarely used in Indonesian, where kelinci is the most common equivalent.)

name: lindung
description: (Used mostly by ethnic Javanese but appears in dictionaries as an Indonesian word.)

name: monyét
description: (In Malaysian there is no general term for ‘monkey’, but many hyponyms.)

name: tawon
description: Para-counterpart (The form appears to have the nomalizing suffix -an, but if any affixation occurred, it was in the donor language.)

name: bekicot
description: (Although strictly speaking denoting a certain kind of snail, the term is commonly used for all kinds of snails.)

name: jénggot
description: (Sideburns and beard on cheeks are called jambang.)

name: janggut
description: (Sideburns and beard on the cheeks are called jambang.)

name: belakang
description: Para-counterpart (This is technically the term for ‘back’, but it is used mostly in the figurative sense of the back part of something.  For body parts, Indonesians use punggung for the upper back and pinggang for the lower back.)

name: lengan
description: (Colloquially, tangan is often used for the arm as well as the hand.  The words lengan and tangan may be related etymologically.)

name: susu (1)
description: Para-counterpart (Until recently this was the general word for ‘female breast’, but now rarely used in this sense, having been replaced in formal contexts by payudara, and in informal contexts by regional words such as tetek.)

name: payudara
description: Sub-counterpart (Used in literary and medical contexts; e.g. ‘breast cancer’ is kanker payudara.)

name: maag
description: (Human stomach; used in medical contexts, e.g. sakit maag ‘stomach ache’)

name: meninggal
description: (‘To die’ and ‘dead’ are not distinguished in Indonesian.)

name: tenggelam
description: (There is no word for ‘dying from suffocation by submersion’, as distinct from ‘to be submerged’.  The former meaning can be expressed by mati/meninggal tenggelam ‘to die by sinking’.)

name: matang
description: (Used with reference to cooked food and fruit, as well as figuratively.)

name: masak
description: (More formal term.  Can be used with reference to cooked food as well as fruit.  This root also means ‘to cook’.)

name: dapur
description: Para-counterpart (Originally this word meant ‘tranditional oven’, and later by extension ‘kitchen’.  In modern Indonesian it usually means ‘kitchen’, and ‘oven’ is expressed by the Dutch loanword open.)

name: mencampur
description: Para-counterpart (The two entries for this meaning (campur and aduk) also form a compound: mencampuradukkan ‘to mix’.)

name: menumbuk
description: Para-counterpart (While not literally meaning ‘to crush’, this is best match for the Meaning Description.)

name: menghancurkan
description: Para-counterpart (While this form literally means ‘to crush’, Indonesians normally use tumbuk ‘pound’ in contexts where English speakers would use ‘to crush’.)

name: (buah) ara
description: (Refers to native species of ficus as well as  Mediterranean figs (which are not widely known in Indonesia).)

name: olive
description: (Used only for pickled olives.  Olive fruit in the context of oil is called zaitun.)

name: tuak
description: (Usually refers to home-made fermented drinks made from sap or juice of the sugar palm or the coconut, and in some regions from rice.)

name: memakai
description: Super-counterpart (This is the most general term for putting on or wearing clothes.)

name: mengenakan
description: Super-counterpart (This is the formal term for putting on clothes.  Informally, pakai ‘use’ is used.)

name: bilik
description: (In Indonesian this word mostly means ‘plaited bamboo, partition made of plaited bamboo’, but in Malaysian it’s the usual term for ‘room’.)

name: ladang
description: Sub-counterpart (The best match for ‘field’, but not the best match for typical context (M4), which would be kebun.   For ‘wet rice field, paddy’ see sawah.  PAN *qumáH ‘garden, cultivated field, swidden’, is reflected in the form (h)uma ‘dry field’, which is now rarely used in standard Indonesian, although it is widely used in vernacular dialects of Malay.  An open field (either fallow or for purposes other than agriculture) is lapangan or padang, both nonloanwords.)

name: kebun, kebon
description: Sub-counterpart (The best match for the typical context (M4).)

name: membabat
description: Super-counterpart (This term is used mostly for tall grass growing in the open, not for grass growing in a garden or a field.  There are many other terms for cutting or clearing vegetation in Indonesian, none of them identical to ‘mow’.  However by far the most common way to express this is by using the root potong ‘cut’.)

name: arit
description: Sub-counterpart (The common tool used for reaping (rice) is ani-ani, a small knife ‘hidden’ in the palm for cutting rice stalks one by one, so as not to frighten the rice goddess.  Sickles and scythes exist but are less common.)

name: sabit
description: Sub-counterpart (The common tool used for reaping (rice) is ani-ani, a small knife ‘hidden’ in the palm for cutting rice stalks one by one, so as not to frighten the rice goddess.  Sickles and scythes exist but are less common.)

name: celurit, clurit
description: Sub-counterpart (The common tool used for reaping (rice) is ani-ani, a small knife ‘hidden’ in the palm for cutting rice stalks one by one, so as not to frighten the rice goddess.  Sickles and scythes exist but are less common.)

name: menebahkan
description: Super-counterpart (In rice cultivation, threshing is separated into two distinct activities.  First, the rice ears are tied into bundles and beaten on a flat surface.  This is called menebahkan (padi).  Then the grain are beaten with wooden instruments to separate the chaff from the grain.  This is called menumbuk (padi).  (Padi is the term for rice before it has been threshed and husked).)

name: menumbuk
description: Super-counterpart (In rice cultivation, threshing is separated into two distinct activities.  First, the rice ears are tied into bundles and beaten on a flat surface.  This is called menebahkan (padi).  Then the grain are beaten with wooden instruments to separate the chaff from the grain.  This is called menumbuk (padi).  (Padi is the term for rice before it has been threshed and husked).)

name: terigu
description: (Terigu refers to processed wheat for consumption.  Wheat as a plant in the field is gandum.)

name: gandum
description: (Gandum refers to wheat in the field.  Wheat processed for consumption is terigu.  Colloquially, gandum also refers to processed whole wheat.)

name: nasi
description: Sub-counterpart (There are many ways of saying ‘rice’ in Indonesian, but this is the one that matches the meaning in the Meaning Despcription (M3).)

name: menguraikan
description: Super-counterpart (The more specific term menguraikan means ‘to untangle’, not to untie a tie made on purpose.)

name: menggebrak
description: (The term for pounding with an instrument is menumbuk.  To punch someone is meninju (formally) or menonjok.)

name: membelah
description: Sub-counterpart (This is the commonly used term for chopping wood, because with every hack, the relevant piece of wood gets cut into two pieces.  The Indonesian word for ‘to chop’ is mencincang, but it is not used in the context of chopping wood given in M4.)

name: menikam
description: (A formal word, used specifically for stabbing with a sharp instrument.)

name: membalikkan
description: (The specific term for ‘to turn one’s head’ is menoléh.)

name: memecahkan
description: (Used especially for brittle substances which shatter, like glass or clay.  For substances that tend to break into fewer pieces the root patah is used; for long objects that break in two, putus.)

name: menekan
description: (The most general term for applying pressure.  Widely used figuratively.)

name: kencana
description: (Used only attributively, especially in commercial names.)

name: menganyam
description: Sub-counterpart (To make a basket or a mat.)

name: meramin
description: Sub-counterpart (While suitable for the Meaning Description (M3), this word is rarely used; the word menganyam is much more common.)

name: permadani
description: Super-counterpart (This word is used mostly in stories and fables.  Rugs and carpets were not normally used in Indonesia.  The type of rug Indonesians are mostly likely to be familiar with is sejedah, ‘prayer rug’.  A modern nonreligious rug is karpet.)

name: sejedah, sajadah
description: Sub-counterpart (This is the most salient equivalent of ‘rug’ in the Indonesian environment.)

name: membélokkan
description: (The specific term for ‘to turn one’s head’ is menoléh.)

name: berpaling
description: (‘To turn one’s head’ is menoléh; this is the verb that would be used in the typical context given in M4.)

name: putar balik
description: (Commonly used for vehicles, but not for humans.)

name: terbit
description: (This word doesn’t match with the meaning of M2, but is the word that would be used in the typical context (M4).)

name: menendang
description: Sub-counterpart (The most commom term for kicking.)

name: menyépak
description: Sub-counterpart (This is the word used for kicking a ball, as in the Typical Context (M4); however, the general word for kicking is menendang.)

name: berjogét
description: Sub-counterpart (Used especially for lively dances, both traditional and modern.)

name: memanjat
description: (Frequently the verb naik ‘go up’ is used for this meaning, including for climbing trees.)

name: berangkat
description: (This means specifically ‘to leave on a trip’.  Often Indonesians use pergi ‘go’ where  English ‘leave’ would be used.  The transitive verb for ‘to leave’ is meninggalkan.)

name: mengungsi
description: Sub-counterpart (This is the word that suits best the typical context (M4).)

name: membawa
description: Super-counterpart (The most general term for ‘to carry’; however, its meaning is much wider.)

name: menggéndong
description: Sub-counterpart (This is the term used most commonly used for carrying a baby.  Indonesian has more than a dozen different terms for carrying, depending on how the carrying is done.)

name: membawa
description: (This is the term which most generally translates ‘bring’.)

name: mengantar(kan)
description: Sub-counterpart (Possible semantic development: to make something visible > to produce something > to bring, deliver)

name: memimpin
description: Sub-counterpart (In the Typical Context (M4), none of the words which commonly translate ‘lead’ would be used.  Rather, membawa (bring) or mengantar (accompany) would be used.)

name: menuntun
description: Sub-counterpart (This is the word most suitable for the typical context (M4).)

name: mendorong
description: (In Malaysia the word has similar but different meanings.)

name: jalan
description: Super-counterpart (For ‘road’ or ‘street’, jalanan can also be used, but not for ‘path, trail, way’)

name: marga (2)
description: (Used in official terminology, e.g. Jasa Marga ‘Toll Road Authority’, Dinas Bina Marga ‘Road Building Authority’.  The unmarked equivalent is jalan.)

name: titi, titian
description: Sub-counterpart (In the Indonesian village scene, this is far more salient than jembatan, used for masonry bridges.)

name: keréta
description: (There are various terms for specific types of horse-drawn carriages; most of these are loanwords.)

name: gandar
description: (Rarely used in Indonesia, but appears in dictionaries; in use in Malaysia.)

name: poros
description: Super-counterpart (Now used mostly figuratively; an actual axle is usually as.)

name: as
description: (Most commonly used term for car axle.)

name: perahu lesung
description: Sub-counterpart (Used for traditional Indonesian dug out canoes. Called so because its shape is like a mortar. American-type canoes are called kano.)

name: mendarat
description: (Originally used for boats and ships, now for aircraft too.)

name: mengantar(kan)
description: (This word is often used with the meaning of ‘to take’, but not in the sense of the meaning description (M3).)

name: mempekerjakan
description: (Although there are several Indonesian terms for hire/employ’, they are rarely used, and periphrastic expressions are used instead.  To hire an object rather than a person is menyéwa, of Sanskrit origin.)

name: mengupahi
description: (Although there are several Indonesian terms for hire/employ’, they are rarely used, and periphrastic expressions are used instead.  To hire something rather than someone is menyéwa.)

name: menggaji
description: (Although there are several Indonesian terms for hire/employ’, they are rarely used, and periphrastic expressions are used instead.  To hire something rather than someone is menyéwa.)

name: kedai
description: (This is the common word for ‘shop’ in Malaysia.  It is known in Indonesia too, where toko is the usual equivalent.)

name: puing
description: Sub-counterpart (Best match with Typical Context, although sisa ‘remains, rest’ is much more common.  The ruins of a building are called reruntuhan,  from Sundanese ruruntuhan, and this is the counterpart that would most probably be used in the sentence given in M4.)

name: mengumpulkan
description: Super-counterpart (This word has the closest meaning to ‘gather’, but cannot be used for gathering mushrooms as in the Typical Context given in M4. For gathering mushrooms, the word memetik ‘to pick’ would be used.)

name: samping
description: Sub-counterpart (Although this is not a direct counterpart of the meaning in M2, it is the word that would be used to translate in the typical context (M4).)

name: awal
description: (Colloquially, pagi ‘morning’ and cepat ‘fast’ are used with the sense of ‘early’.)

name: dini
description: (Colloquially, pagi ‘morning’ and cepat ‘fast’ are used with the sense of ‘early’.)

name: mula
description: (The adverbial expression (as used in Typical Context) is mula-mula ‘at the beginning’)

name: lagi
description: Super-counterpart (The sense of ‘again’ is often conveyed by placing kembali ‘return’ before the verb.)

name: siang (2)
description: (The meaning ‘midday’ does not occur in Malaysia, where tengah hari (lit. middle day) is used for this meaning.  This is also used in Indonesia, but to a lesser extent.)

name: kemarin dulu
description: (Commonly expressed with the phrase dua hari yang lalu ‘two days ago’.)

name: musim dingin
description: (Indonesia has two seasons, a dry season (musim kemarau) and a rainy season (musim hujan).  However, the terms for the four seasons of temperate zones are widely known.)

name: musim semi
description: (Indonesia has two seasons, a dry season (musim kemarau) and a rainy season (musim hujan).  However, the terms for the four seasons of temperate zones are widely known.)

name: musim panas
description: (Indonesia has two seasons, a dry season (musim kemarau) and a rainy season (musim hujan).  However, the terms for the four seasons of temperate zones are widely known.)

name: musim gugur
description: (Indonesia has two seasons, a dry season (musim kemarau) and a rainy season (musim hujan).  However, the terms for the four seasons of temperate zones are widely known.)

name: mengendus
description: (The closest match for ‘to sniff’, although not commonly used.)

name: terasa
description: Super-counterpart (More commonly, speakers would say “rasanya X”, lit. ‘its flavor is X’.  The transitive counterparts are mencicipi (based on a Javanese loanword), and mengecap.)

name: bersinar
description: Sub-counterpart (To emit light (rather than reflect it), or to be perceived as emitting light (like the moon))

name: menyilaukan
description: (While not a direct equivalent of the LWT meaning, this word is the closest match for the typical context (M4).)

name: meraba
description: Super-counterpart (This is the verb that would be used in the given Typical Context.)

name: empuk
description: (This word is the closest match for the typical context (M4).)

name: baik
description: (Bagus is more about external qualities, and baik about internal qualities.)

name: bagus
description: (Bagus is more about external qualities, and baik about internal qualities.)

name: jelas
description: (Clear (weather) is terang or cerah; clear (water) is bening or jernih.  None of these are loanwords.)

name: mencurigai
description: (The fact that the antepenult vowel of the base curiga did not undergo reduction to schwa marks it as a loanword.)

name: enggak, nggak, gak, ga
description: (This colloquial word is now making its way into formal Indonesian; can be found in journalese but not yet in very formal contexts.)

name: menegur
description: Super-counterpart (This is the most commonly used word for scolding.  However literally it means ‘to address someone’; the negative connotation is inferred.)

name: teman
description: (This is the most common word for ‘friend’ in Indonesian.  In Malaysian it is considered literary; the common word there is kawan, which is still used in Indonesia, but considered literary.)

name: pengadilan
description: (The general term for court of law.)

name: ketemu
description: (This originally colloquial form is now becoming accetaple in formal discourse.)

name: bertikai
description: (Of all words related to this meaning, this one suits the Typical Context best.)

name: perdamaian
description: (The adjective damai ‘peaceful’ is more common than the noun perdamaian ‘peace’.)

name: narapidana
description: Sub-counterpart (A convict, prisoner convicted of a crime.)

name: luncas
description: (A rarely used word; normally, the periphrastic expression tidak kena ‘not to hit (the target)’ is used.)

name: menjerat
description: (A trap is perangkap, related to tangkap ‘catch’.  The root perangkap is rarely used verbally. In the Typical Context (M4), one would simply use menangkap ‘to catch’.)

name: menjebak
description: (A trap is perangkap, related to tangkap ‘catch’.  The root perangkap is rarely used verbally. In the Typical Context (M4), one would simply use menangkap ‘to catch’.)

name: undang-undang
description: (This is the sense that most suits the meaning description and typical context.)

name: mahkamah
description: Sub-counterpart (Used for higher courts; lower courts are pengadilan.)

name: zina(h)
description: (To commit adultery or cheat on one’s partner is selingkuh, from Javanese.)

name: déwa
description: (Goddess is déwi, also from Sanskrit.  God (capital G) is Tuhan or Allah.  The latter was borrowed from Arabic.)

name: rumah ibadah
description: (There are various terms for houses of worship of different religions.)

name: korban
description: Super-counterpart (There is no special term for ‘the ritual killing of an animal’; one uses the word potong ‘cut’ (here meaning ‘slaughter’), followed by the animal’s name, e.g. potong kerbau ‘to sacrifice a buffalo’.  The verb berkorban means ‘to make a (personal, figurative) sacrifice, to sacrifice oneself’; pengorbanan is the act of (figuratively) sacrificing.)

name: beribadah
description: (The base of transitive verb memuja ‘to worship’ is puja, of Sanskrit origin.)

name: sembahyang
description: Sub-counterpart (Means ‘to recite a formulaic prayer’,  as opposed to composing one’s own prayer, which is beroda.)

name: berdoa
description: Sub-counterpart (Usually refers to praying to God (of the monetheistic faiths).)

name: sholat
description: Sub-counterpart (Specifically, formulaic prayer in Arabic recited five times a day by observant Muslims.  But frequently used as a verb, even though strictly speaking this does not conform to standard Indonesian grammar.)

name: mencaci-maki
description: Sub-counterpart (The two constituents of this compound both mean ‘to abuse verbally’, but are rarely used by themselves.)

name: kamar kecil
description: Exact counterpart (Originally a euphamism, now this is the most commonly used term for a toilet.)

name: ada, berada
description: Para-counterpart (There is no direct equivalent of ‘to be’, but this is the closest match.)

name: menjadi
description: Para-counterpart (There is no direct equivalent for ‘to be’ in Indonesian; menjadi literally means ‘to become’, but is used in some context where European languages would use the equivalent of ‘to be’, for example to express professions: dia menjadi guru ‘he is a teacher’.)

name: makaate
description: (An alternative is boofolo (uncommon earlier loan from Swahili))

name: hiinuwee
description: Sub-counterpart (Other alternatives: kishida (Swahili) black cloth skirt, mirindu (Swahili) short skirt with many folds)

name: burungeti
description: (The native word inqwaari is less often used)

name: dandúu doo'
description: (There are many words for parts of the roof)

name: nuundu
description: (The native word slahhmo is also used.)

name: nada
description: (Alternatively sokooni from Swahili ‘at the market’ is used.)

name: shikeru
description: (despite its appearance, it is not a loan)

name: kemuri
description: (old form keburi, changes to kemuri, first attested 1074)

name: tomosu
description: (there is a phrase which is often used hi o tsukeru “put on fire”. which may be a fixed expression)

name: onna
description: Exact counterpart (old form omina or womina)

name: otokonoko
description: Exact counterpart (older forms onogo (書記）, ononogo (万葉集) , current form attested in 1711)

name: onnanoko
description: Exact counterpart (older forms onnago (935) and onago (mid-Kamakura), current form attested in 1717)

name: aka-chan
description: (this is a diminuitive, first attested in 1904. In the form akago, the word has been attested since the 11th century.)

name: chichi (1)
description: Exact counterpart (old form chi, attested in 712. The reduplicated form appeared in the 万葉集　(after 8th century).)

name: otōto
description: (older forms oto (712) and otohito (720). Current form first attested in 934.)

name: imōto
description: (older forms imo (712) and imohito (新撰字鏡、around 900), current form first attested in 伊勢物語　(bf. 10th century))

name: senzo
description: (variant sosen 祖先 (1717). Obsolete variant senso  先祖.)

name: otokoyamome
description: Exact counterpart (yamō attested in 書記720)

name: ondori
description: (the prefixoid o- “male” appears as on- here.)

name: buyo
description: Sub-counterpart (Older variant buto (1558), modern variants buyo and buyu (the latter attested in 1736))

name: chō (1)
description: (other forms chōchō 蝶々 (1648), kochō 胡蝶 (818))

name: abara
description: Exact counterpart (abarabone　肋骨　 in 太平記 (14th century), abara in 1746.)

name: sekichū
description: Exact counterpart (variants include sekitsui (1774), sekiryō (14th century))

name: zugaikotsu
description: (zugaikotsu first attested in 1884. variants zugai (1774), tōkotsu (1884). The kan’on variant with tō is also seen in tōgai(kotsu))

name: fukurahagi
description: Exact counterpart (variants fukurappagi (1783), fukurappage (1886), fukurappami (1933). fukurahagi first attested in 1820)

name: shinzō
description: Exact counterpart (First attested variant shin no zō, shinzō first attested around 1358.)

name: kanzō
description: Exact counterpart (First attested variants kan, kan no zō (both in 1477). First mention of kanzō in 1911.)

name: jinzō
description: (obsolete variants jin 腎 (1177) and jin no zō 腎の臓 (1481). Current form first attested in 1283.)

name: hizō
description: (older variants hi 脾 (1177), hi no zō  脾の臓 (1597). present form first attested in 1909.)

name: dankon
description: Exact counterpart (nankon. dankon first attested in 1914)

name: chinko
description: Exact counterpart (variants chinbo (1722), chinboko (1779), chinbō (1786). even more infantile is chinchin (1834). Present form first attested in 1796.)

name: netsu
description: (first attested as nechi. netsu is attested in 1604.)

name: darui
description: Exact counterpart (originally tarui, and even earlier tayui. While the latter was attested in the　万葉集, the former and the present variant might be dialectal of origin. tarui/darui first attested in 1462.)

name: oshi
description: Exact counterpart (originally oushi. Short form attested in 源氏 (1001))

name: you
description: (originally eu (wepu). Present form first attested in 室町中。)

name: gohan
description: Exact counterpart (gohan (first attested in 1793)  is originally a polite variant of han, which fell into disuse. The first polite variant was oban (1579). Both terms were orginally polite feminine speech. Another polite term, gozen, of polite masculine speech, was first attested in 1219.)

name: asameshi
description: Exact counterpart (A more polite variant, asagohan, is a hybrid and first attested in 1599. An obsolete NJ term, asage, was first attested in the beginning of the 11th century.)

name: hirumeshi
description: Exact counterpart (A more polite variant, hirugohan 昼御飯, is a hybrid and first attested in 1910. An obsolete variant is hiruge 昼餉, first attested around 1128.)

name: yūmeshi
description: Exact counterpart (More polite variants, bangohan and yūgohan, were both first attested in 1909. An old NJ term, yūge, was first attested in 1116.)

name: furuu
description: (Also as a compound verb, furuiwakeru 篩い分ける, with the second component meaning “divide”)

name: suribachi
description: Sub-counterpart (ataribachi is a polite term, attested in 1899.)

name: surikogi
description: Sub-counterpart (The variant surigi was attested in 1559.)

name: chiizu
description: (kāzu, from the Dutch, in 1822, later replaced by the English.)

name: rinneru
description: (other variant, based on the English: rinen.)

name: momen
description: (The general term men is attested in the 13th century. The NJ reading kiwata is also attested, 1589.)

name: kazarimono
description: Exact counterpart (another variant, kazari attested in 万葉集（bf. 800))

name: hankachi
description: Sub-counterpart (originally hankachiifu, then clipped to hankachi (first in 1911))

name: borokire
description: Sub-counterpart (Variant boro 襤褸, borokire attested in 1886.)

name: tobira
description: Exact counterpart (to used in the 古事記 (712))

name: isu
description: (At first the word was pronounced ishi, which changed to isu under the influence of spoken Chinese (concurrent with the advent of Zen) in the 15th century. The current variant was first attested in 1439.)

name: taku
description: Sub-counterpart (Since it usually refers to a dining table, shokutaku is often used.)

name: kizamu
description: (A variant is the compound verb kirikizamu)

name: sasu
description: (A variant is the compound verb tsukisasu　突き刺す)

name: potopoto ochiru
description: (More formal NJ terms include shitataru 滴る.)

name: itsudemo
description: Exact counterpart (This has to be accompanied by a negated verb form.)

name: shinpai
description: Exact counterpart (Originally this was a NJ phrase kokorokubari, which then was read as a SJ word.)

name: mata
description: Exact counterpart (Often followed by the topic marker wa)

name: shōtai
description: Exact counterpart (originally written 請待 (syaudai in Classical Japanese). Later on 招待 became more common.)

name: nageami
description: Exact counterpart (Also read toami as a hybrid.)

name: kangofu
description: Sub-counterpart (kangonin1872, changed by law to present form)

name: toire
description: Exact counterpart (Original form toiretto, first attested in 1928, the short version is first attested in 1952.)

name: otearai
description: Exact counterpart (variant tearai, although when used with the meaning of “toilet”, the polite prefix is usually added.)

name: kan
description: (this is a rare case of an English loan which has retained its ateji)

name: shinbun
description: (variant shinbunshi was used for “newspaper” as well.)

name: kyoku
description: Exact counterpart (variant kakyoku 1092, specifically referring to sung melodies.)

name: cha
description: (Often accompanied by the polite prefix o-.)

name: da
description: (Different copulas according to politeness level include desu, dearu, gozaimasu)

name: -palɨmi
description: Exact counterpart (‘son-in-law of a woman’ also)

name: -palɨmi
description: Exact counterpart (‘son-in-law of a man’ also)

name: enɨlɨ
description: Super-counterpart (to drink or to eat juicy fruits)

name: putuputuli
description: Sub-counterpart (does’nt contain the meaning of “nai” as body part)

name: amɨ (1)
description: Para-counterpart (applied to countable and no countable entities)

name: tupulu
description: Para-counterpart (the colours of the spectrum have a different distribution)

name: tikile
description: Para-counterpart (the colours of the spectrum have a different distribution)

name: mɨlato
description: Para-counterpart (designs a specific group of mixed Kali’na)

name: àrgə̂m
description: Sub-counterpart (millet is the common grain for Kanuri)

name: liessk
description: (generic ‘wife or husband who lost her/his partner’)

name: skała
description: (A regular word form is absent because there was no need for naming this meaning.)

name: paliś
description: (Verbal aspect: imperf.; other forms: spaliś (perf.), spalowaś (imperf.))

name: gasyś
description: (Verbal aspect: imperf.; other forms: gasnuś (perf), zagasyś (perf.), wugasyś (perf.))

name: ženiś se
description: (Verbal aspect: imperf.; other forms: wóženiś se (perf.))

name: muter(ka)
description: (Also moter(ka) and often as diminutive with Suffix -ka.)

name: źiśi
description: (In this meaning a plural-word; if there is only on child  you have to choose “syn“ (son) or “źowka“ (daughter) instead of the singular-word „góle“ (see 2.27).)

name: dwójnika
description: (Dual; if there are several twins: dwójniki (plural); Derivation from the numeral 2)

name: prědowniki
description: (Plural; in singular you have to differenciate male/female: prědownik/prědownica)

name: pótomniki
description: (Plural; in singular you have to differenciate male/female: pótomnik/pótomnica)

name: šwogor
description: Sub-counterpart (An older loanword is „šwar“ (from Middle Low German).)

name: roźeńca
description: (Old derivation from „rod“ (birth); another formal variant is „roźelnica“)

name: samadruga
description: (Also: samodruga; as for [-hum] there are different word for different animals (no loanwords).)

name: napity
description: (Originally participle of the perf. verb „napiś se“ (drink so much that you get drunk))

name: warjony
description: (Originally participle of the imperf. verb „wariś“ (to cook))

name: šklicka
description: (Formally a deminutive from „šklica“ , which is (also as a deminutive form) based on „škla“ (compare 5.33))

name: jěšnica
description: (Original (older) meaning: liver sausage. Old derivation from „jětša“ (liver; compare 4.45))

name: zelenina
description: (Normally used was the concrete denotation; derivation from the adjective „zeleny“ (green))

name: kulka
description: (Formally deminutive from „kula“. Original meaning: small ball (germ. kleine Kugel))

name: pyto
description: (The root is proto-slavonic but with another meaning (germ. Fessel))

name: rozdźěliś
description: (Normally used are words that name the concrete action: to lay, to spread, ...)

name: starcyś
description: (There are some different verbs for this action.)

name: wumožyś
description: (Old derivation on basis of „móc“ (to be able))

name: znicyś
description: (There are different words for special contexts. This word is a general one.)

name: tužyca
description: (An older word and basis for the today’s derivation is: tuža)

name: zmužny
description: (An older form and basis of the today’s: mužny)

name: póžedaś
description: (An older form and basis of the today’s: žedaś)

name: ideja
description: (There are several words with slightly different meanings (compare German: Idee, Begriff, Vorstellung). Its not clear what is originally meant here.)

name: pśikazaś
description: (In older times also used without prefix.)

name: zwóliś
description: (In older times also used without prefix.)

name: sudnistwo
description: (Only historically analyzable (an older word is „sud“ as in Russian).)

name: cart
description: Sub-counterpart (An older meaning was „demon (of wind)“. The later and today’s meaning is a Christian reinterpretation.)

name: masonàndro
description: (the ‘eye of day’ metaphor for ‘sun’ is very common in Austronesian languages)

name: vehivàvy
description: (vehivàvy is presumably created in analogy with the reduplicated form lehilàhy, cf. 2.23)

name: rahalàhy
description: Para-counterpart (constituent parts are inherited from Proto Austronesian; ràha- < *ra- ‘HON’ + *aka older sibling’)

name: izàho
description: (iz- (< Proto Austronesian *i ‘PM’) + àho ‘1SG’. These constituent parts are inherited from Proto Austronesian (cf. Dahl 1951:234-238).)

name: ianào
description: Sub-counterpart (i- (Proto Austronesian *i ‘PM’) + a- (?) + -nao ‘2SG’. Cf. Dahl (1951:239-242); cf. also Maanyan, Samihim -nu ‘2SG.POSS’, and Maanyan naun ‘2PL’; cf. also Iban nuan ‘2SG’, which may point to a wider spread of this pronoun within Borneo)

name: ialàhy
description: Sub-counterpart (constituent parts i and làhy are both inherited from Proto Austronesian)

name: mpiàndry
description: (mpi- possibly < *ulun ‘person’ + *fi- nominalising prefix (Adelaar in press b))

name: kisòa
description: (kosòa is a variant form; ki- looks like a NOUN prefix through false analogy)

name: rabìtro
description: (the first syllable of this word is erroneously analysed as an HON prefix ra- (which according to Dez (1964) appears in many European animal names). This explains the occurrence of a variant form bìtro.)

name: bìtro
description: (Cf. the variant form rabìtro from which bitro is derived through false analogy of ra- as a HON prefix)

name: vòmbona
description: (somehow related to Proto Malayo Polynesian *buŋbuŋ ‘roof ridge’?)

name: ramèva
description: (Abinal and Malzac (1970) also give angamenavàva (mèna ‘red’, vàva ‘mouth), of which ramèva is supposedly a short form)

name: lohàlika
description: (*alika is cognate to Maanyan alep ‘knee’ < South East Barito *alǝb)

name: tsìnay
description: (this word reflects Proto Austronesian *Cinaqi ‘intestines’, which in turn must be derived from *Caqi ‘faeces’ through infixation of *-in- (reference unknown [Blust?]; a morphological relationship between the words for ‘faeces’ and ‘intestines’ is also found in various non-Austronesian languages in mainland South East Asia).)

name: milèlaka
description: (root of Malagasy lèlaka is /lèlaf/-, as in the passive form lelàf-ina; cf. Maanyan lelap ‘flame’ and nilap ‘to lick’; lèlaka and lelap/nilap could be related to Proto Malayo Polynesian *dilaq ‘tongue’ but their root-final -f-/-p remains unexplained)

name: manonòfy
description: (May somehow be related to Proto Austronesian *Sepi but the /o/ corresponding to *e is irregular.)

name: ràtra
description: Sub-counterpart (cf. (Central East Barito) Dusun Deyah daat, (South East Barito) Dusun Witu raʔat ‘bad’ (Hudson 1967:75))

name: fandrìana mihàntona
description: (this phrase is given in several dictionaries but it may not be idiomatic)

name: zàvatra boribòry kitsoloha
description: (looks made up but is listed as such in three independent dictionaries)

name: manjàvona
description: (cf. Dusun Malang (South East Barito) ǰaun ‘fog’, Dusun Dejah (Central East Barito) ǰaβun ‘cloud’, Lawangan (North East Barito) ǰaaun ‘cloud; fog’ (Hudson 1967))

name: làkana
description: (This word has several cognates in Borneo, cf. Iban langkan ‘dug-out keel-piece of boat’ (Richards 1981))

name: mampiàsa
description: (àsa ‘work’ is adopted from Sanskrit via Malay, cf. 9.12)

name: toèrana
description: (Cf. (North East Barito) Taboyan tuwɨt, Lawangan tuwut ‘to sit’ (Hudson 1967:71))

name: havìa
description: (havìa could be a reflex of Proto Austronesian *wiRi ‘left(-hand)’ (with prefix *ka- > ha-) but final -a remains unexplained)

name: làvitra
description: (could reflect Proto Austronesian *laSud ‘towards the sea’, cf. a parallel phonological development in *daSun ‘leaf’ > ravina ‘id.’)

name: sìvy
description: (initial s- is unexpected in inherited vocabulary)

name: àmpy
description: (must be related to Malay sampay ‘to reach’)

name: fìndra fo
description: (also ìndra fo (ìndra is apparently a short form of the root fìndra))

name: nihavìany
description: Super-counterpart (àvy ‘to come’ has a Maanyan cognate hawi ‘to come, arrive’)

name: ìza
description: (1. cf. Maanyan hie ‘who?’; 2. REL pronoun ‘who’ is izày)

name: andèvo
description: (cf. Dahl (1951:312); Sakalava Malagasy has à corresponding form on/dèvo, maintaining *u in the first syllable)

name: mpanòmpo
description: (tòmpo is inherited from Proto Malayo Polynesian)

name: mpisarìvy
description: Sub-counterpart (the root of this word is derived from French service, cf. Dez (1965))

name: manòmpo
description: Para-counterpart (tòmpo is inherited from Proto Malayo Polynesian)

name: fahavàlo
description: (originally ‘the eighth house of the sikidy divination’ which represents ‘the enemy’)

name: àdy
description: (Dempwolff (1938) related this word to Tagalog ali ‘to dispute someone’s right’)

name: fìntana
description: (related to Maanyan wintan ‘fishhook’; the irregular initia f- (instead of expected v-) is presumably due to back-formation, cf. mamintana ‘to fish with a fishhook’ (Dahl 1951:332))

name: mitsàra
description: (mitsàra must be the result of false analogy: *bicara (a noun) > *mitsàra (used verbally) > mi-tsàra)

name: mifàdy hànina
description: (fàdy and hanina are both inherited from Proto Austronesian)

name: fifidiànana
description: (the nominal ending -anana remains unexplained; historically, it seems to be a concatenation of *-an + *-an)

name: xin1 (1)
description: Super-counterpart (no exact equivalent; possible partial equivalents sixiang 思想，yijian 意见 ,opinion, yitu 意图, jingshen 精神 ,spirit’)

name: choroy
description: Exact counterpart (a bird similar to the parrot)

name: ḻaweṉ
description: Sub-counterpart (medicines derived from plants and natural elements)

name: ürkülen
description: Sub-counterpart (to be tired (some specific part of the body))

name: patay
description: Sub-counterpart (The bread that is made of algarroba flour)

name: masa
description: Super-counterpart (It has been documented as a verb ‘to make the dough’  (Spanish ‘amasar’))

name: sumel
description: Sub-counterpart (in past generations, in areas with abundant horses, the kind of shoe made with the hide of horses)

name: choñchoñ
description: Sub-counterpart (recipient with kerosene and a wick. The same word is used to designate a being with evil characteristics: it takes the shape of a winged head and no body that wanders around at night)

name: chaküra
description: Super-counterpart (armed field with legumes, vegetables, and even cattle)

name: füṉ
description: Super-counterpart (fruit of a plant, also flesh)

name: katrüketranün
description: Sub-counterpart (it:.‘ketra’ means what has been sown, by extension the Mapuche word for wheat (plant introduced by the  Europeans))

name: füṉ
description: Super-counterpart (fruit of a plant, also flesh)

name: ko
description: Super-counterpart (water, also refers to the ‘juice or sap of a plant or tree’)

name: mütrongün
description: Sub-counterpart (to strike or hit somebody or something on purpose)

name: palolpaloltun
description: Sub-counterpart (beat; bang on something (like a door).)

name: pachüqün
description: Sub-counterpart (spread something like grains on a surface)

name: ngürin
description: Sub-counterpart (press something down into  a recipient.)

name: wellimün
description: Exact counterpart (to make flow from one container to another)

name: entun
description: Super-counterpart (to take out; also to earn)

name: itrotripa
description: Sub-counterpart (In front of something big like a house (FM, p. c.))

name: püllü
description: Sub-counterpart (the spirit of a living person)

name: poyen
description: Sub-counterpart (have a strong affection or deep feeling for someone)

name: mallma
description: Exact counterpart (arrogant; having or showing too much pride (proud in a negative sense))

name: küpa
description: Sub-counterpart (auxiliary; invariable form used in verbal construction, e.g.:  küpa in ‘I want to eat’)

name: feyentun
description: Exact counterpart (originally meant ‘obey’, but since evangelization means ‘believe’)

name: azümün
description: Sub-counterpart (to learn manual work, by hand)

name: azümazümtun
description: Sub-counterpart (to prove or practice for learning)

name: wimtun
description: Para-counterpart (to be accostumed, have the habit of)

name: pezan
description: Sub-counterpart (find or meet by chance, come across)

name: üyew
description: Sub-counterpart (It indicates more distance than” tüyew”)

name: kʊlikan
description: Super-counterpart (The word kʊlika:n in Oroqen means ‘insect’ in general.)

name: kadɪwʊn
description: Sub-counterpart (Oroqen has another word ʃandʊr for ‘scythe’, which is a borrowing from Chinese. The Chinese word is 釤刀 shàn dāo ‘scythe’.)

name: kad-ur
description: Sub-counterpart (Oroqen has another word ʃandʊr for ‘scythe’, which is a borrowing from Chinese. The Chinese word is 釤刀 shàn dāo ‘scythe’.)

name: ʃand-ʊr
description: Sub-counterpart (Oroqen has another word ʃandʊr for ‘scythe’, which is a borrowing from Chinese. The Chinese word is 釤刀 shàn dāo ‘scythe’.)

name: kaqlaaq’
description: (Cu Cab (1998) has the morphemes reversed as laq'kaaq, lit. 'join-lightning/thunder'. Cu Cab (1998) also has remleb' ha', lit. ‘join-rain’. Cu Cab (1998) also has xookiq'ab' and xuq'aq'ab'.)

name: saaj ixqa’al
description: (Anonymous (2004) has t’ujixq, tuq’ixq, tuq’ix "joven, señorita, muchacha, soltera, virgen".)

name: jachoj ib’
description: (The verbal form in Sam Juárez et al. (1997)  is kanab’ank ib’ for divorciarse.)

name: k’ajol
description: Exact counterpart (Sources for Kaufman & Justeson (2003) give the meaning ‘hijo de hombre’; possibly this is a better translation.)

name: lut
description: Exact counterpart (Freeze (1975) has lach for 'los gemelos'.)

name: kab’lal
description: Super-counterpart (Kockelman (2001) has komun-ej as 'family', which is Spanish loan word (from comunidad) that uses the inalienable possessive suffix -ej, perhaps the only case of a loanword that does this.)

name: laa’o, aa’o, ha’o
description: Exact counterpart (There is no difference between inclusive and exclusive.)

name: laa’o, aa’o, ha’o
description: Super-counterpart (There is no difference between inclusive and exclusive.)

name: chib’aat
description: Exact counterpart (Anonymous (2004) has this same for ‘cabra’.)

name: kaxlan
description: Exact counterpart (tilan is said by Freeze (1975) to be an eastern dialectal form and kaxlan is the western.)

name: suk
description: Exact counterpart (Sedat (1955) gives sik. Sok and sook are other variants.)

name: k’utub’
description: Sub-counterpart (Possibly derived from a verb root k’ut meaning “to show”. The basic meaning refers to a handspan, thus the semantic relationship. -Vb’ is a non-productive instrumental suffix.)

name: kuk
description: Exact counterpart (Attested in Sam Juárez et al. (1997) in compounds referring to small and large squirrels.)

name: ismal
description: Super-counterpart (The underived form occurs in other forms such as ismrix ‘velludo, peludo’. *isim is proto-Mayan)

name: salb’a
description: Exact counterpart (Cu Cab (1998) says a variant form is sakb'a.)

name: ru'uj aq'
description: Exact counterpart (The form aq’ historically means ‘tongue’ and preserves this in even closely related languages, but does not occur as a free form with this meaning.)

name: aq (1)
description: Exact counterpart (Humberto Cu Cab (1998) has b'een aq.)

name: re maqab’
description: Exact counterpart (Sam Juárez et al. (1997) states that “Para algunos, "re maq ab" es la superficie del pecho y "maqab" es todo el pecho.)

name: kun
description: Exact counterpart (Cu Cab (1998) has kunutz' and pirich.)

name: may
description: Super-counterpart (There are several words for specific kinds of poison; this is the only word in the main source which has a general meaning.)

name: q'aaneq
description: Exact counterpart (Freeze (1975) has q'e:l (cEqueel in original orthography). The Anonymous (2004) has q'aajenaq. Cu Cab (1998) has q'aynaq and q'umet.)

name: we'ej
description: Exact counterpart (Cu Cab (1998) has we'ej and wi'ej for 'escasez'.)

name: chikleb’
description: Exact counterpart (derived from a root *chik ‘to cook’)

name: nawaaj
description: Super-counterpart (Sam Juárez et al. (1997)  has nab’aaj and Anonymous (2004)  has jotzleb’; separate entries for these have not been included.)

name: k’aan
description: Super-counterpart (It is not certain that this is used for latches.)

name: uutz’u’uj
description: Super-counterpart (The basic meaning appears to be ‘flower’, but maybe the extended sense is ‘adornment’ or ‘thing that smells good’.)

name: sik'lik
description: Exact counterpart (This seems to basically be a noun meaning ‘cigar’, but here used as a verb.)

name: toon
description: Super-counterpart (toon is additionally translated as ‘tronco’ in Sedat (1955).)

name: panchola
description: Sub-counterpart (The Spanish word is a local one.)

name: jorok
description: Super-counterpart (The gloss for the intransitive version explicitly mentions glass.)

name: jachok
description: Super-counterpart (The glosses are distributed over different sources as follows: partir, pegar un machetazo, separar (Sam Juárez et al. 1997); partir, aserrar, rajar, dividir, fraccionar (ALMG 2004))

name: soq'e'k
description: Exact counterpart (probably used mostly about soft things)

name: apuunk
description: Exact counterpart (Sam Juárez et al. (1997) has apunk.)

name: wiq'laak
description: Exact counterpart (The same root appears in Sam Juárez et al. (1997), but only in a participial form.)

name: q'ajk
description: Super-counterpart (Sedat (1955) specifies the meaning as ‘volver: regresar (a la casa propia o pueblo de uno)’.)

name: k’amok b’e
description: Exact counterpart (One consultant said b’eh, but others used b’e.)

name: q’unuk
description: Exact counterpart (Freeze (1975) has quetzo [ketzo] and gives ketzoonk as the modern equivalent of quetzo.)

name: to’nink
description: Exact counterpart (This seems to be ‘to lend’ rather than to borrow, though the consultant insisted it was okay.  Sam Juárez et al. (1997) has to’nink also as ‘prestar.’)

name: k'as
description: Exact counterpart (Anonymous (2004) has k'asom for "deuda (en general).")

name: sa’ xk’atq
description: Exact counterpart (Sam Juárez et al. (1997) also has pak’alil for ‘lado’.)

name: nim xkelam
description: Exact counterpart (Humbert Cu Cab (1998) has jukun.)

name: amaq' tenamit
description: Exact counterpart (This is a so-called difrasismo, a Mesoamerican phenomenon where two near-synonyms are joined for form an expression)

name: sumal
description: Exact counterpart (Sam Juárez et al. (1997) has sumaal.)

name: ewu
description: Sub-counterpart (This possibly refers to the afternoon, should be checked.)

name: k'a
description: Exact counterpart (Kockelman (2001) has ru for 'bitter' or 'spicy'.)

name: k'ojk'o xch'ool
description: Super-counterpart (This is based on a common Mesoamerican idiom of 'seated heart' meaning 'content'.)

name: kaqal
description: Super-counterpart (For 'jealous', Kockelman (2001) gives kaq ch’oolej (lit. ‘red hearted’).)

name: q'etq'et
description: Super-counterpart (This is a negative quality in the culture.)

name: b'ach' b'ach'
description: Super-counterpart (Note that ‘proud’ is a negative concept in rural Middle America, similar to ‘haughty’)

name: liib'r
description: Exact counterpart (There is a homonym for this, meaning ‘weight’ (libra); the two are merged in the same entry in the source.)

name: nimla tenamit
description: Super-counterpart (Tenamit probably means ‘city’ as well as ‘town’.)

name: simaj
description: Super-counterpart (Freeze (1975) has pocche (in original orthography) for 'bow', i.e., ‘bent-wood'. He mentions the root poc meaning ‘arquear en esta forma.’)

name: puub'
description: Super-counterpart (Originally meant 'blowgun' and was later applied to the gun.)

name: poopol
description: Super-counterpart (Also means ‘municipalidad’ or ‘alcaldía’, cf. Sam Juárez et al. (1997).)

name: raqol aatin
description: Exact counterpart (PLFM (2000) has raqol chaq’rab’ for 'juez'.)

name: mayej
description: Super-counterpart (This is the same root as may ‘tobacco’. The suffix -ej appears to be the same is as the one used to indicate ‘unpossessed’ with cetain kinship and bodypart terms. The form is classified as ‘unanalyzable’ since -ej can be regarded as inflexional rather than derivational.)

name: kuyuk sa’
description: Super-counterpart (Anonymous (2004) has k'ajb'ak. Freeze (1975) has (in original orthography) eucquehic, and mentions elqe'ik as 'ritos de abstinencia, ayuno.’)

name: retali xyo’lajik
description: Exact counterpart (yo'lajik is ‘nacimiento’ or ‘cumpleaños,’ which derives from the verb yo'laak, 'to be born'.)

name: taql
description: Super-counterpart (The meaning ‘mandado, mensaje, mando’  is that of Sam Juárez et al. (1997))

name: čeydeː
description: Super-counterpart (There is no noun with the meaning ‘breakfast’, instead the verb ‘to drink tea’ is used.)

name: čeydeː
description: Super-counterpart (There is no noun with the meaning ‘supper’, instead the verb ‘to drink tea’ is used.)

name: tart
description: Super-counterpart (With the meaning of ‘grind’ this is a sub-counterpart, because it is restricted to grinding grain; however, the verb is also a super-counterpart, because it means ‘pull’ in addition to ‘grind’ (and is also used for ‘to smoke’).)

name: χayɨhar
description: (This word refers to skis, not snowshoes.)

name: χallaːn küöχ
description: Exact counterpart (This is only used when one needs to be specific; in general, küöχ means both ‘green’ and ‘blue’.)

name: ot küöχ
description: Exact counterpart (This is only used when one needs to be specific; in general, küöχ means both ‘green’ and ‘blue’.)

name: séki
description: Super-counterpart (The core sense of this word is a verb meaning ‘shake’. However, the “sékíwáta” means ‘rough water’ according to Rountree et al. 2000, which is why it is given here.)

name: sómba
description: Exact counterpart (Rountree et al. 2000 do not give ‘shadow’ as a meaning for this word, but de Groot 1981 does.)

name: wómi
description: Sub-counterpart (The word for ‘man’ appears to be used to indicate ‘male’, for both people and animals. Since ‘man’ is the core meaning, I’m calling it a sub-counterpart to ‘male’, but this analysis strikes me as tenuous.)

name: miíi
description: Exact counterpart (Clearly related to the word for child. Unclear which should be treated as the loan. See the child. I’m treating that as the loan and this as an extension.)

name: tíngífóo
description: (This word was chosen as generic based on de Groot 1977.)

name: alála
description: (Based on examination of de Groot 1977 and Rountree et al. 2000, this seems like the most generic word for this type of bird.)

name: hógífóu
description: (This is the only form given as generic by both Rountree et al. 2000 and de Groot 1977.)

name: aliá
description: (This word is from de Groot 1977 who in other cases seemed less accurate with species than Rountree et al. 2000.)

name: dágúsíka
description: (Example sentence in de Groot 1977 indicates this word is most likely to mean ‘flea’ of the words listed under vlo.)

name: kúkútúlábu
description: (This word has a double entry in Rountree et al. 2000: ‘scorpion’ and ‘type of scorpion’.)

name: fínga u fútu
description: (Word drawn from entry in de Groot 1977.)

name: básu (1)
description: (de Groot’s 1981 Saramaccan-Dutch dictionary gives this form for the spleen. However, his 1977 Dutch-Saramaccan dictionary gives básu-béè which could mean ‘bottom-stomach’ or maybe ‘spleen-stomach’. If básu-béè is correct, this word is not a borrowing, but an Saramaccan-created compound.)

name: tumá
description: (Only word indicated as having only sexual meaning in Rountree et al. 2000.)

name: baási
description: (This meaning for the word was drawn from de Groot 1977.)

name: apakí
description: (This word is listed under kom in de Groot 1977.)

name: sikö́tííki
description: (Could this really mean ‘saucer’? The cup meaning comes from Rountree et al. 2000.)

name: nján (2)
description: (This word is listed under maaltijd in de Groot 1977.)

name: alibí
description: (I am treating the kidney and the bean as being the same word in Saramaccan. However, this is clearly a borderline case.)

name: peéli
description: Sub-counterpart (This word Is a hyponym. No other clearly singular form can be found.)

name: féki
description: (When this word is followed by puu ‘pull’, it means ‘to erase’.)

name: jaa
description: (This meaning for this word is known from consultant work.)

name: faáka
description: (There does not seem to be a general word for ‘to follow’. de Groot 1977 gives equivalent of ‘go with’. This word is used in contexts of tracking animals, for example.)

name: mandá
description: (I’m treating this as a separate word from mandá ‘command’.)

name: tjubí
description: (This meaning of the word drawn from de Groot 1977.)

name: básusë
